content.value:
If you have arthritis, you’re probably no stranger to tossing and turning at night. Joint pain can make it tough to fall asleep, stay asleep or both. In fact, up to 80% of people with arthritis report some type of issue with their z’s.1 
So, what’s going on? “There are several reasons why people in pain can have a difficult time sleeping,” says Michael Guma, DO. He’s the medical director of rheumatology for Optum in Rutherford, New Jersey.  
For one, changing positions at night can cause pain. With some forms of arthritis, such as rheumatoid arthritis, joints can stiffen up when you’re not moving, says Dr. Guma. Then when you shift position during the night, those joints hurt.  
Unfortunately, bad nights can set up a vicious cycle. “Lack of sleep is like an amplifier for your pain. It can be like turning the pain volume knob to a higher number,” Dr. Guma says.  
And for older adults, missing out on sleep can increase the odds of falls or accidents, as well as memory issues and depression, according to the National Institute on Aging.2   
Bottom line, says Dr. Guma: “It’s so important to get that good night of sleep.” Here’s how to get started.

children.text: Adding more green tea to your diet can be a simple and enjoyable way to reap its potential health benefits while considering the associated risks. Here are some practical tips to incorporate green tea into your daily routine:

If you're new to green tea, it's best to start with a moderate intake of one to two cups per day. This allows your body to adjust to the caffeine content and reduces the risk of potential adverse effects.
Opt for high-quality loose-leaf green tea or tea bags without additives or flavorings. This ensures that you are consuming pure green tea and avoiding any potentially harmful substances.

To maximize the health benefits of green tea, pay attention to the brewing process. Use water that is hot but not boiling, and steep the tea for about 2-3 minutes. This helps prevent the release of excessive tannins, which can make the tea bitter.

If you find the taste of plain green tea too mild or grassy, consider adding natural flavorings. You can try adding a slice of lemon or a sprig of mint to enhance the flavor without adding any extra calories or sugar.

Consider green tea supplements as an alternative way to incorporate the health benefits of green tea into your diet. Green tea supplements provide a concentrated dose of beneficial compounds, such as catechins and antioxidants, without the need to consume multiple cups of tea.

overview.value: In today’s fast-paced work environments, the practice of taking smoke breaks at work has become a subject of both discussion and contention. As employees strive to balance their professional responsibilities with personal habits, employers must grapple with the challenge of accommodating these needs while maintaining workplace productivity and ensuring the well-being of their workforce. This article delves into the complex landscape of smoke breaks at work, shedding light on their impact on employee productivity and health.
